You can&#39;t return more than one type from a stream.  So you would need to house the information in a class or some other structure (e.g. a map).  Here I create a class to hold the results. `SummaryStatistics` does something similar.
```
int[] nums = {5,5,5,5,5};
Info&lt;Integer&gt; results = Arrays.stream(nums).boxed().reduce(new Info&lt;&gt;(),
        Info::add,
        (a,b)-&gt;a); // combiner - required but not used in this case

System.out.println(results.getList());
System.out.println(results.areAllTheSame());
```
prints
```
[5, 5, 5, 5, 5]
true
```

- The `add()` method both adds the value to the list and increments count if the `item` matches the `first` value added. `count` defaults to `1`. It also returns `this` to simplify the `reduce` method since the accumulator is expected to return the updated value.
- reduce first creates a class in which the values are stored.
- `allAreTheSame()` returns the `boolean` resulting from comparing the count to the list size.
```
class Info&lt;T&gt; {
    private T first = null;
    private List&lt;T&gt; list = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    private int count = 1;

    public Info&lt;T&gt; add(T item) {
        list.add(item);
        if (first == null) {
            first = item;
        } else if (first == item) {
            count++;
        } 
        return this;
    }
    
    public List&lt;T&gt; getList() {
        return list;
    }

    public boolean areAllTheSame() {
        return count == list.size();
    }
}

You could use a teeeing collector to do both tasks simultaneously. Something like:

    int[] nums = {6,5,5,5,5};
    HashMap&lt;String, Object&gt; result = Arrays.stream(nums)
                                           .boxed()
                                           .collect(Collectors.teeing(
                                                   Collectors.toList(),
                                                   Collectors.filtering(i -&gt; i != 5,Collectors.counting()),
                                                   (myList, count) -&gt; {
                                                       HashMap&lt;String, Object&gt; map = new HashMap();
                                                       map.put(&quot;myList&quot;, myList);
                                                       map.put(&quot;myBool&quot;, count == 0);
                                                       return map;})
                                                   );

    System.out.println(result.get(&quot;myList&quot;));
    System.out.println(result.get(&quot;myBool&quot;));

**But just because you can doesnt mean you should** 

It is much more understandable and cleaner not to combine two operations that give two completely different results, but to do them separately. There is nothing wrong with:

    List&lt;Integer&gt; list = Arrays.stream(nums).boxed().toList();
    boolean allFives = list.stream().allMatch(i -&gt; i == 5);

